I will answer shortly, what you are doing is undefined behavior.

In the way your structure is defined, compiler is allow to assume that you will never use more than `sizeof int64_t` for the variable member `int64_t c`. So if you try to write more that `sizeof int64_t`(aka. `sizeof c`) on `c`, you will have an out of bound in your code. This is the case because `sizeof "aaaaaaaa"` > `sizeof int64_t`.

The point is, whatever the size you will allocate with your `malloc()`, the compiler is allow to suppose that you will never use more than `sizeof int64_t` in your `strcpy()` or `memcpy()` call. Because you send the address of `c` (aka `int64_t c`), not the structure.

TL;DR: You are trying to copy 9 bytes to a type consisting of 8 bytes(we suppose that byte is an octet). (From [@Kcvin][1])

If you want something similar use flexible array members from C99:

    #include <stdio.h>
    #include <stdlib.h>
    #include <string.h>
    
    typedef struct {
      size_t size;
      char str[];
    } string;
    
    int main(void) {
      char str[] = "aaaaaaaa";
      size_t len_str = strlen(str);
      string *p = malloc(sizeof *p + len_str + 1);
      if (!p) {
        return 1;
      }
      p->size = len_str;
      strcpy(p->str, str);
      puts(p->str);
      strncpy(p->str, str, len_str + 1);
      puts(p->str);
      memcpy(p->str, str, len_str + 1);
      puts(p->str);
      free(p);
    }


